{
  "title": "5.3 RECOMMENDATIONS",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "88c4b53f014154a3",
      "text": "**(i)** Creation of grazing reserves. There is an urgent need to create gazing reserves in different geographical locations in the country. Furthermore, the existing ones in Oyo State should be made functional urgently. Existence of grazing reserves in places like Kwara, Kogi, and Benue States will reduce the pressure on pastoralists to migrate to the south during the dry season."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "834d866cfbfb1b66",
      "text": "**(ii)** Re-establishment of cattle tracks. The re-establishment of cattle tracks throughout the country should be of the utmost priority to complement the introduction of grazing reserves. In this regard, it is noteworthy that Oyo State Government has taken a positive step in tackling the problem by creating cattle tracks and routes in the State (see annex-vi-) It is essential that the tracks are put to use urgently and should be wide enough to minimise the instance of cattle straying into farms. Cattle routes must be resuscitated as a matter of urgency throughout the country and when operational, they must be properly “policed” to ensure that pastoralists use them."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "954b7e1004796ede",
      "text": "**(iii)** Involvement of cattle owners in finding a lasting solution to the conflict.  It is amazing that cattle owners who are mostly based in the northern part of the country hardly show any  interest in what happens to their stock when they move southwards during the dry season in search of pasture. Given the calibre of these cattle owners, it is not out of place for them to lobby or even pressurize the Federal and State Governments to find lasting solutions to the conflicts by creating functional grazing zones in different parts of the country."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "38066cf1779db876",
      "text": "**(iv)** Collaboration of Government at various levels. There is need for governments at all levels to address the conflicts between farmers and pastoralists more urgently and decisively. The Federal, State and Local Governments need to collaborate to find a lasting solution to this problem, especially because of the security implications of the incessant clashes between farmers and pastoralists. Indeed, the conflicts have assumed a serious dimension in places like Plateau, Benue,  Nasarawa and Kaduna States where violent clashes are now an epidemic occurring almost daily and resulting in huge loss of lives and properties. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "a92ebc2588dc4c04",
      "text": "**(v)** Establishment of Stakeholders’ forum. Stakeholders’ fora should be established at the local level to design a bottom up approach solutions to the problem. Such form should be designed to meet regularly and be empowered to deal with local problems. If these fora are functional, many of the problems would be resolved peacefully before they escalate. They could also serve as an instrument of early warning system to higher authorities."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e4eb91683430ced3",
      "text": "**(vi)** Establishment of more nomadic schools for Fulani’s children. The essence of this is to ensure that as many Fulani children as possible are exposed to formal western education, thus freeing them from  pasturing duties at tender ages, especially if it is remembered that part of the complaints of farmers was that young Bororo Fulani herders had problems controlling their herds."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5f21d0058666c96e",
      "text": "**(vii)** Exploring the possibility of a farmers’ insurance policy. Farmers should explore the possibility of taking insurance cover for their crops so that they can be compensated should their crops be destroyed. If they have insurance cover, not only would their losses be minimized the conflicts between them and pastoralists would be reduced."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "17939894d34e6342",
      "text": "**(viii)** Perception issue. This is a problem that can only abate with time through the process of interaction. This is why the stakeholders’ meeting discussed earlier would be very useful. When people interact with one another regularly over time, they appreciate one another more and the negative perception tends to change. The stakeholders’ meeting should, therefore, be encouraged to hold regularly."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4c9ae91d792b2f00",
      "text": "**(ix)** Need to modernise animal husbandry. In the long run, the solution to the conflict is to introduce modern method of animal husbandry which uses intensive and not extensive grazing. In this connection, consideration should be given to the establishment of cattle ranches across the country. The Nigerian nation can borrow the time tested problem solving mechanisms of developed countries where it is rare for farmers and pastoralists to engage in conflicts. It is noteworthy that a milk manufacturing company in the country is pioneering the use of smallholder farmers in raising cattle in their farms, using the intensive grazing method.    "
    },
